rmk:
ID based on circumstances.  Several years ago, I heard a similar sound
(similar to an explosive call of Japanese green woodpecker)
in the same season and in the same district.  The sound was initially
a mystery but was resolved because a song of ruddy kingfisher (Halcyon coromanda)
followed in one occasion.  It was on fall migration.
Although I am not completely sure this recording is the same sound
which I heard several years ago, the close coincidence of the season
and environment support this identification.
The call is probably what is referred to as "an explosive rattle"
in Mark Brazil's "Birds of East Asia".
Very likely corresponds to XC90083 (flight call).
In the foot of low mountain in the suburb of Kyoto city.
Convincing identification in XC278281.
Ruddy Kingfisher was seen several times in this area of mangove, but the bird remained hidden whilst calling. Probably same bird as  XC193833

rmk: I believe the barking call heard in this recording is a Ryukyu Scops Owl (there's also a frog in the background), but my focus was the whistly series of falling notes. I heard this vocalization several times on Iriomote, and also on Kuroshima. It seemed to be produced only around dawn and dusk (the latter, in the case of this recording). There were multiple individuals present at the time and location of this recording, which was taken at dusk in a thick forest near the coast, but I did not get a visual, and they seemed a ways off, perhaps midway up the trees or in the canopy, though it was hard to be sure. The recording has not been modified.

I heard two voices in twilight and successfully recorded the second one.
The first voice reminded me of ruddy kingfisher (Halcyon coromanda),
but the second voice (this recording) is not typical for this species.
Ten minutes later I heard and recorded a typical voice of this species
in a slightly different place ( XC194242).
I wonder this may be a variation of song (or call) of this species.

rmk:
Voice heard immediately after XC672769 and it looks most likely
the same bird also issued this voice (there was no other bird voice).
The microphone was probably not in the direction of the voice
(the voice was heard to the ears more clearly).
Strong insect background and it might be difficult to recognize
the voice.  The sounds are slightly rising 3 kHz notes, strongest
at 0:15 and 0:20.  Weaker and slightly lower-pitched sounds at
0:01 and 0:07.  I'm not familiar with this type of vocalization
of Halcyon coromanda and comments are welcomed.
